  <brief_title>A Randomized, Controlled Study of the Safety and Preventive Efficacy of Oral Ganciclovir When Used in Conjunction With An Intravitreal Ganciclovir Implant in the Treatment of Cytomegalovirus Retinitis</brief_title>
  <official_title>A Randomized, Controlled Study of the Safety and Preventive Efficacy of Oral Ganciclovir When Used in Conjunction With An Intravitreal Ganciclovir Implant in the Treatment of Cytomegalovirus Retinitis</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Roche Global Development</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>NIH AIDS Clinical Trials Information Service</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      To demonstrate the efficacy of oral ganciclovir in preventing new cytomegalovirus (CMV)
      disease in AIDS patients with unilateral CMV retinitis treated with an intravitreal
      ganciclovir implant. To compare safety and tolerance, time to progression, quality of life,
      and survival among patients treated with an intravitreal ganciclovir implant, with and
      without oral ganciclovir, versus standard intravenous (IV) ganciclovir therapy.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Patients receive intravitreal ganciclovir implant plus oral ganciclovir, intravitreal implant
      alone, or IV ganciclovir.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
